{"id":3399,"date":"2020-05-20T21:17:00","date_gmt":"2020-05-20T21:17:00","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/?p=3399"},"modified":"2020-09-03T17:57:04","modified_gmt":"2020-09-03T17:57:04","slug":"core-collapse-in-massive-scalar-tensor-gravity","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/2020\/05\/20\/core-collapse-in-massive-scalar-tensor-gravity\/","title":{"rendered":"Core collapse in massive scalar-tensor gravity"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>If General Relativity is too boring, couple it to something else. In this paper we study what happens to stellar collapse and supernova explosions if gravity is transmitted not only with the usual metric of Einstein&#8217;s theory (aka the graviton) but also an additional quantity. If this extra scalar field has a mass, it dramatically impacts the emitted gravitational waves&#8230; Which means that maybe, one day, one can use gravitational-wave data to figure out if scalar fields are coupled to gravity. Here we try to explore all the related phenomenology of stellar collapse with a large set of simulations covering the parameter space. And the overall picture is remarkably neat and simple!<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Roxana Rosca-Mead, Ulrich Sperhake, Christopher J. Moore, Michalis Agathos,&nbsp;<strong>Davide Gerosa<\/strong>, Christian D. Ott.<br>Physical Review D 102 (2020)&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/journals.aps.org\/prd\/abstract\/10.1103\/PhysRevD.102.044010\" target=\"_blank\">044010<\/a>.<br>arXiv:<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/arxiv.org\/abs\/2005.09728\" target=\"_blank\">2005.09728<\/a>&nbsp;[gr-qc].<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>If General Relativity is too boring, couple it to something else. In this paper we study what happens to stellar collapse and supernova explosions if gravity is transmitted not only with the usual metric of Einstein&#8217;s theory (aka the graviton) &hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/davidegerosa.com\/202